		<li id="comment-380" class="comment byuser comment-author-elementalsystems odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1">
			<article id="div-comment-380" class="comment-body">
				<footer class="comment-meta">
					<div class="comment-author vcard">
						<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/?s=56&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/?s=112&amp;d=mm&amp;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-56 photo avatar-default' height='56' width='56' />						<b class="fn"><a href='http://elementsrevisited.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>elementalsystems</a></b> <span class="says">says:</span>					</div><!-- .comment-author -->

					<div class="comment-metadata">
						<a href="http://localhost:8888/microfiction.co.za/2010/08/05/an-introduction-to-a-dream/#comment-380">
							<time datetime="2010-08-17T15:32:30+00:00">
								August 17, 2010 at 3:32 pm							</time>
						</a>
											</div><!-- .comment-metadata -->

									</footer><!-- .comment-meta -->

				<div class="comment-content">
					<p>Great idea and lovely rhythms, I really love the lists of characters, things, consequences and so on. The repetition works really well in this form. Good fun to read out loud with vigour.<br />
Also like that it is about Stories in general and their role in our lives.</p>
<p>I find (and like) a lot of ambiguity about who exactly the &#8216;motley crew&#8217; are in the last verse: the grown up children; the role-model fantasy hero&#8217;s within; ideas and dreams; childhood fantasies.</p>
<p>I think the punctuation in poetry is not open to criticism so long as it doesn&#8217;t conflict with the meter of the words (which for me it doesn&#8217;t).</p>
<p>Poetry is easy to crit and hard to write but:<br />
In terms of this rhythm I would remove the unicorn/born rhyme in &#8216;The dragon’s egg, a unicorn, the place where forest nymphs are born&#8217; as it throws me when reading it aloud (non of the verses rhyme in this spot). Similarly the last two lines miss the rhyme that ass the other verses have something like:</p>
<p>Ready to leap into your dreams when you start to yawn<br />
Where their wisdom, wit and wiles will make the hours fly ‘till dawn.<br />
OR<br />
Ready to leap into your dreams where the adventure still goes on<br />
Watch their wisdom, wit and wiles &#8217;til the night is gone.</p>
				</div><!-- .comment-content -->

